tools_called.args:
{"query": "To control Crassula helmsii, how do chemical methods like herbicides compare in effectiveness to physical methods like using lightproof barriers or salt water?", "summary": "Chemical herbicide methods show variable effectiveness for controlling Crassula helmsii. Glyphosate reduced C. helmsii in seven studies, with one study showing a 98% reduction when glyphosate was combined with diquat (Action 1279). When glyphosate was applied after covering plants with carpet, it resulted in an 80% reduction (Action 1279, 1313). Three out of four studies found that diquat or diquat alginate reduced cover or eradicated submerged C. helmsii, though one small trial found no effect (Action 1279). Other herbicides showed partial effectiveness: dichlobenil led to partial biomass reduction in one out of two studies, while terbutryne partially reduced biomass of submerged plants (Action 1279). Hydrogen peroxide did not control C. helmsii in controlled tank trials (Action 1281).

Physical methods using lightproof barriers demonstrated strong effectiveness. Five before-and-after studies found that covering C. helmsii with black sheeting or carpet strips eradicated or severely reduced plant cover, though progressive recolonization occurred at two sites where eradication was initially reported (Action 1294). Aquatic dyes to reduce light levels did not reduce C. helmsii coverage (Action 1293).

Salt water treatment showed consistent effectiveness, with two replicated controlled container trials and two before-and-after field trials finding that seawater eradicated C. helmsii (Action 1288).", "action_ids": ["1279","1281","1288","1293","1294","1313"]}

